         <exercise>
            <title>Euler Equations</title>
            <statement>
                <p>An important class of second-order linear differential equations are equations of the form
                    <me>t^2 y'' + \alpha t y' + \beta y = 0,</me>
                where <m>t \gt 0</m> and <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are real constants.  An equation of this form is called an <em>Euler equation</em>.
                    <ol>

                        <li><p>Show that the substitution <m>x = \ln t</m> transforms an Euler equation into an equation of constant coefficients.</p></li>

                        <li><p>Solve the equation
                            <me>t^2 y'' + 4ty' + 2y = 0.</me></p></li>

                    </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>Show that
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} &amp; = \frac{dx}{dt} \frac{dy}{dx}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{d^2y}{dt^2} &amp; = \left( \frac{dx}{dt} \right)^2 \frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + \frac{d^2x}{dt^2} \frac{dy}{dx}.</mrow>
                    </md></p>
            </hint>
        </exercise>


         <exercise>
            <title>Higher Order Linear Equqtions with Constant Coefficients</title>
            <statement>
                <p>The characteristic equation of the <m>n</m>th order linear differential equation
                    <me>y^{(n)} + a_{n - 1} y^{(n-1)} + \cdots a_1 y' +  a_0 y = 0</me>
                is
                    <me>\lambda^n + a_{n - 1} \lambda^{n-1} + \cdots a_1 \lambda +  a_0 = 0.</me>
                For example, the characteristic equation of 
                    <me>\frac{d^3 y }{dt^3} - 6 \frac{d^2 y}{dt^2} + 11 \frac{dy}{dt}  - 6y = 0</me>
                is
                    <me>\lambda^3 - 6 \lambda^2 + 11 \lambda - 6 = 0.</me>.
                This equation factors as <m>(\lambda - 1)(\lambda - 2)(\lambda - 3) = 0</m>.  Since the roots of the characteristic equation are <m>\lambda_1 = 1</m>, <m>\lambda_2 = 2</m>, and <m>\lambda_3 = 3</m>.  As with second-order linear differntial equations, we can immediately write down our solution as
                    <me>y = c_1 e^t + c_2 e^{2t} + c_3 e^{3t}.</me>
                    <ol>

                        <li><p>Find the general solution of the equation <m>y^{(4)} - 9 y'' + 20y = 0</m>.</p></li>

                        <li><p>Find the general solution of the equation <m>y''' - 6 y'' + 2y' + 36y = 0</m>.</p></li>

                        <li><p>Find the general solution of the equation <m>y''' - y'' + y' - y = 0</m>.</p></li>

                    </ol>
                    In general, we can always factor the characteristic polynomial over the complex numbers; however, this may be very difficult to do in practice.  We are often forced to numerical techniques, especially for systems of very high order.</p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>Show that
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} &amp; = \frac{dx}{dt} \frac{dy}{dx}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{d^2y}{dt^2} &amp; = \left( \frac{dx}{dt} \right)^2 \frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + \frac{d^2x}{dt^2} \frac{dy}{dx}.</mrow>
                    </md></p>
            </hint>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

    <subsection number="no" xml:id="secondorder01-subsection-sage">
        <title>Solving Second Order Linear Equations with Sage</title>

        <p>Second order homogeneous linear differential equations with constant coefficeints can be solved sybolically using <em>Sage</em>. For example,
            <me>x'' + 2 x' + x = 0</me>
        can be solved using the following Sage commands.</p>

        <sage>
            <input>
            t = var('t')  
            x = function('x')(t)
            DE = diff(x,t,2) + 2*diff(x,t) + x == 0
            desolve(DE, [x,t])
            </input>
            <output>
            _K1*e^(-t) + _K2*e^(-2*t)
            </output>
        </sage>

        <p>We can even solve initial value problems such as
        	<md>
        		<mrow>x'' + 2 x' + x \amp = 0</mrow>
        		<mrow>x(0) \amp = 1</mrow>
        		<mrow>x'(0) \amp = 2</mrow>
        	</md></p>

        <sage>
            <input>
            t = var('t')
            x = function('x')(t)
            DE = diff(x,t,2) + 2*diff(x,t) + x == 0
            desolve(DE, [x,t], ics=[0, 1, 2])
            </input>
            <output>
            4*e^(-t) - 3*e^(-2*t)
            </output>
        </sage>

        <p>Of course, we can add a forcing term to our initial value problem,
        	<md>
        		<mrow>x'' + 2 x' + x \amp = t \cos 2t</mrow>
        		<mrow>x(0) \amp = 1</mrow>
        		<mrow>x'(0) \amp = 2</mrow>
        	</md></p>

        <sage>
            <input>
            t = var('t')
            x = function('x')(t)
            DE = diff(x,t,2)+3*diff(x,t)+2*x == t*cos(2*t)
            desolve(DE, [x,t], ics=[0, 1, 2])
            </input>
            <output>
            -1/100*(5*t - 12)*cos(2*t) + 1/200*(30*t - 7)*sin(2*t) + 97/25*e^(-t) - 3*e^(-2*t)
            </output>
        </sage>

    </subsection>

